         <abstract>
            <p>Let $S = \langle X_0,\ldots, X_m \rangle$ be an $m$-simplex in $R^n$. We define "bisection" of $S$ as follows. We find the longest edge $\langle X_i, X_j \rangle$ of $S$, calculate its midpoint $M = (X_i + X_j)/2$, and define two new $m$-simplexes $S_1$ and $S_2$ by replacing $X_i$ by $M$ or $X_j$ by $M$. Suppose we bisect $S_1$ and $S_2$, and continue the process for $p$ iterations. It is shown that the diameters of the resulting simplexes are no greater then $(\sqrt 3/2)^{\lbrack p/m \rbrack}$ times the diameter of the original simplex, where $\lbrack p/m \rbrack$ is the largest integer less than or equal to $p/m$.</p>
          </abstract>
